SIMPLE: square
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Square
<hw>Square</hw> <pr>(skw⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>esquarre</ets>, <ets>esquierre</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧querre</ets>
a carpenter's square (cf. It. <ets>squadra</ets>), fr. (assumed) LL.
<ets>exquadrare</ets> to make square; L. <ets>ex + quadrus</ets> a
square, fr. <ets>quattuor</ets> four. See <er>Four</er>, and cf.
<er>Quadrant</er>, <er>Squad</er>, <er>Squire</er> a square.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The corner, or angle,
of a figure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A parallelogram
having four equal sides and four right angles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, anything which is square, or nearly so</def>;
as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A square piece or fragment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He bolted his food down his capacious throat in <qex>squares</qex>
of three inches.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A pane of glass.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>A certain number of lines, forming a portion of
a column, nearly square; -- used chiefly in reckoning the prices of
advertisements in newspapers.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Carp.)</fld>
<def>One hundred superficial feet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An area of four sides, generally with houses on each
side; sometimes, a solid block of houses; also, an open place or area
for public use, as at the meeting or intersection of two or more
streets.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The statue of Alexander VII. stands in the large <qex>square</qex>
of the town.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mech. & Joinery)</fld> <def>An instrument having at
least one right angle and two or more straight edges, used to lay out or
test square work. It is of several forms, as the T square, the
carpenter's square, the try-square., etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hence, a pattern or rule.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Arith. & Alg.)</fld> <def>The product of a number
or quantity multiplied by itself; <as>thus, 64 is the <ex>square</ex> of
8, for <mathex>8 ⟦times⟧ 8 = 64</mathex>; the <ex>square</ex> of
<mathex>a + b</mathex> is <mathex>a<exp>2</exp> + 2ab +
b<exp>2</exp></mathex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Exact proportion; justness of workmanship and
conduct; regularity; rule.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They of Galatia [were] much more out of <qex>square</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have not kept my <qex>square</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A body of troops formed in a
square, esp. one formed to resist a charge of cavalry; a squadron.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The brave <xex>squares</xex> of war.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Fig.: The relation of harmony, or exact agreement;
equality; level.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We live not on the <qex>square</qex> with such as these.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>The position of planets
distant ninety degrees from each other; a quadrate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>The act of squaring, or quarreling; a
quarrel.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>The front of a woman's dress over the bosom,
usually worked or embroidered.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>fair and square</b></col> <cd>in a fair, straightforward,
and honest manner; justly; <as>as, he beat me <ex>fair and
square</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Geometrical square</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Quadrat</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Hollow
square</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a formation of troops in the
shape of a square, each side consisting of four or five ranks, and the
colors, officers, horses, etc., occupying the middle.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Least square</b></col>, <col><b>Magic
square</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Least</er>,
<er>Magic</er>, etc.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>On the square</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Upon the square</b></col></mcol>, <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>in an open, fair manner; honestly, or upon honor; justly.</cd>
<mark>[Obs or Colloq.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>at right angles.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>On the square with</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Upon the
square with</b></col></mcol>, <cd>upon equality with; even with.</cd>
<au>Nares.</au> -- <col><b>To be all squares</b></col>, <cd>to be all
settled.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Dickens.</au> -- <col><b>To be
at square</b></col>, <cd>to be in a state of quarreling.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Nares.</au> -- <col><b>To break no
squares</b></col>, <cd>to give no offense; to make no difference.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>To break squares</b></col>, <cd>to depart
from an accustomed order.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>To see how
the squares go</b></col>, <cd>to see how the game proceeds; -- a phrase
taken from the game of chess, the chessboard being formed with
squares.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>L'Estrange.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Square</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Square
<hw>Square</hw> <pr>(skw⟦acir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>Having four equal sides and four right angles;
<as>as, a <ex>square</ex> figure</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Forming a right angle; <as>as, a <ex>square</ex>
corner</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having a shape broad for the height, with
rectilineal and angular rather than curving outlines; <as>as, a man of a
<ex>square</ex> frame</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Exactly suitable or correspondent; true;
just.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She's a most triumphant lady, if report be <qex>square</qex> to
her.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Rendering equal justice; exact; fair; honest;
<as>as, <ex>square</ex> dealing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Even; leaving no balance; <as>as, to make or leave
the accounts <ex>square</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Leaving nothing; hearty; vigorous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By Heaven, <qex>square</qex> eaters.⟦br⟧
More meat, I say.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>At right angles with the mast or
the keel, and parallel to the horizon; -- said of the yards of a
square-rigged vessel when they are so braced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Square</ex> is often used in self-explaining
compounds or combinations, as in <ex>square</ex>-built,
<ex>square</ex>-cornered, <ex>square</ex>-cut, <ex>square</ex>-nosed,
etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Square foot</b></col>, <cd>an area equal to that of a
square the sides of which are twelve inches; 144 square inches.</cd> --
<col><b>Square knot</b></col>, <cd>a knot in which the terminal and
standing parts are parallel to each other; a reef knot. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Knot</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Square
measure</b></col>, <cd>the measure of a superficies or surface which
depends on the length and breadth taken conjointly. The units of square
measure are squares whose sides are the linear measures; as,
<xex>square</xex> inches, <xex>square</xex> feet, <xex>square</xex>
meters, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Square number</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Square</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 6.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Square root of
a number</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Square root of a
quantity</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>that number or
quantity which, multiplied by itself, produces the given number or
quantity.</cd> -- <col><b>Square sail</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>a four-sided sail extended upon a yard suspended by the middle;
sometimes, the foresail of a schooner set upon a yard; also, a cutter's
or sloop's sail boomed out. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Sail</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Square stern</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a stern having a transom and joining the counter
timbers at an angle, as distinguished from a <xex>round stern</xex>,
which has no transom.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Three-square</b></col>,
<col><b>Five-square</b></col>, etc.</mcol>, <cd>having three, five,
etc., equal sides; as, a <xex>three-square</xex> file.</cd> --
<col><b>To get square with</b></col>, <cd>to get even with; to pay
off.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Square</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Square
<hw>Square</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Squared</conjf> <pr>(skw⟦acir⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Squaring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF.
<ets>escarrer</ets>, <ets>esquarrer</ets>. See <er>Square</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To form with four equal sides and
four right angles.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form with right angles and straight lines, or
flat surfaces; <as>as, to <ex>square</ex> masons' work</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To compare with, or reduce to, any given measure or
standard.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To adjust; to regulate; to mold; to shape; to fit;
<as>as, to <ex>square</ex> our actions by the opinions of
others</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Square</qex> my trial⟦br⟧
To my proportioned strength.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make even, so as to leave no remainder or
difference; to balance; <as>as, to <ex>square</ex>
accounts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To multiply by itself; <as>as, to
<ex>square</ex> a number or a quantity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>To hold a quartile position
respecting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The icy Goat and Crab that <qex>square</qex> the Scales.</q>
<rj><qau>Creech.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To place at right angles with the
keel; <as>as, to <ex>square</ex> the yards</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To square one's shoulders</b></col>, <cd>to raise the
shoulders so as to give them a square appearance, -- a movement
expressing contempt or dislike.</cd> <au>Sir W. Scott.</au> --
<col><b>To square the circle</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>to
determine the exact contents of a circle in square measure. The solution
of this famous problem is now generally admitted to be
impossible.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Square</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Square
<hw>Square</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To accord or agree
exactly; to be consistent with; to conform or agree; to suit; to
fit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No works shall find acceptance . . .⟦br⟧
That <qex>square</qex> not truly with the Scripture plan.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go to opposite sides; to take an attitude of
offense or defense, or of defiance; to quarrel.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are you such fools⟦br⟧
To <qex>square</qex> for this?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take a boxing attitude; -- often with
<xex>up</xex>, sometimes with <xex>off</xex>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squarely</ent>⟦br⟧
